Anonymous Wed 12 Apr 2023 20:03:24 No.55731815 Report
Quoted By: >>55732935
>>55731438
Write a lot, delete it all, and write again. It will all look like trash to you, because you are looking for good writing. You will write twenty pages, cringe, delete fifteen, and continue that cycle until eventually, you have excellent work.
For dialogue, try having the conversation in your head, complete with gestures and pauses. People dont talk like robots dispensing info, and people who just met tend to be more formal with eachother.
Dont give up because the first draft was ass.
Write what YOU want to write.
Please do not be one of the weirdos who cant even keep the POV straight because he is typing with one hand.
Anonymous
  • Post
  • Report

Anonymous Wed 12 Apr 2023 20:03:49 No.55731823 Report
Quoted By: >>55732935
>>55731438
Start small, 5k is plenty.

Have some sort of problem to solve or conflict to compromise over.

Make sure the waifur's species/whatever is relevant in some way.

If the story gets away from you, let it go and follow it.

Don't worry that it's going to be garbage. You can't make it better without learning what's wrong and the only way to learn what's wrong is to put it out there and let critics torch it. If you take criticism of your work personally, that's your fault. If you take it as a list of all the places you can improve, your second edition will be better than the average fic from anyone who refuses to listen to his critics.

Pay attention to the basic plot structure. Intro, rising, climax, falling, outro. Don't just write shit to be writing. Have a point greater than AND THEN THEY ALL FUCKED.

It was written by a Boomer furry and it reads like something from prior to the September that Never Ended. The viewpoint character explains to the reader in one early scene that he can't leave Earth forever, he's got to be able to keep his job, because he only has access to email through work computers. Like it's 1988 and the entire office is sharing one Compuserve account, or something like that.

There's one scene I won't spoil where characters previously established as intelligent and competent go completely clownshoes and do some dangerous dumb shit that bites all of them in the ass instantly. I think the author just really wanted to write an action scene with a big gun battle. A 20th Century pulp author named Robinson gave the infamous writing advice, "When the action slows down and you don't know what to do next, drop a body through the skylight." It's a lazy thing for an author to do when he's stretching for what should happen next in his story of the square-jawed private eye and the shifty dame with the secret.

In a sci-fi story about a self-insert closet anthro fetishist learning his loving wife got technomagically zapped into an anthro vixen body and then yiffing her brains out inside an honest-to-God flying saucer, repeatedly, at great length, it left me shaking my head and I was not able to read much further past that scene. You will know it when you see it. It's the scene where the boomer gun autism and cringey pre-Internet gun memes are likely to give even the most jaded /k/ommando a brain hemorrhage.

The story had already veered far from the sci-fi worldbuildan I was hoping for. Never mind explaining what these seeming real-live anthro foxes actually are or where they came form, or what their culture is like, or what other starfaring civilizations there are, let's spend multiple chapters talking about whether the ship's engineer has the hots for the first officer. Because why wouldn't you?

But up to that point, it has its moments.

There are >implications in one of the Spess Focks characters' internal monologues, in which she hopes that the Nice Humans Don't Find Out What We Did to teh Spess Jaguar People who Invaded Our Planet and Enslaved Us. My guess was that they laid the ol' Exterminatus on their asses but I had no details. A genetically engineered plague seems like it'd be beyond their technical means, if their flying saucers have vacuum tube radios and radars. And if they didn't use CRISPR to cook up something special, well, in the real world there are reasons bioweapons haven't seen a whole lot of use. Ethics aside, germ warfare, for all that 20th Century newspapers had lurid headlines about it, is inherently uncontrollable and unpredictable. The selective pressure on your pet germs are going to be for less lethality, because mutations making them less lethal will give the new version of the germ a great evolutionary advantage over the prior version that killed the hosts too fast for it to spread as much as it otherwise might. And, say, if you want a germ that will exterminate an insect plant pest, for example--to step back from the ethical questions of genocide--what if it only kills 90% or 99%? In six months or a year all the members of the species will be descended from the survivors, and your germ doesn't work any more. No, if you want to handle problems like a hostile starfaring polity, quickly and efficiently and permanently, and at scale, then it isn't microbiology or biochemistry you need to call on. It's physics. Can your starships push a nice big rock, like maybe one the size of the Moon, and nudge its orbit so that it collides with their planet? That'd do it. In 1945 the first nuclear weapons had all vacuum tube electronics, because transistors hadn't beeninvented yet. So I'm surprised that the Spess Fockses used biologicals. Did the author go into any detail or did he just say "we found a sooper deadly germ on Generic Jungle Planet #47, lol" ?
